But instead of exploding, the live mortar shell punched a hole in the bodywork and stopped when it hit the rubber tire.

He said: 'I ran off when I saw it and shouted to everyone to keep away, but after half a day when it was still there and hadn't exploded, I went back and took a snap.'

But the un-exploded mortar is reportedly still wedged in car because for the moment it's too dangerous to remove, according to Mr Kassis who posted these images online.

This weekend, deadly fighting between Islamist militias and forces backed by Libya's internationally recognised government forced the closure of an airport in eastern Tripoli, military sources said.

